Here's a concise example:

**XAML:**
```xml
<CollectionView ItemsSource="{x:Bind ViewModel.Products}">
    <CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
        <DataTemplate x:DataType="models:Product">
            <VerticalStackLayout Padding="10">
                <Label Text="{x:Bind Name}" FontSize="18" FontAttributes="Bold" />
                <Label Text="{x:Bind Price, StringFormat='{0:C}'}" FontSize="14" />
            </VerticalStackLayout>
        </DataTemplate>
    </CollectionView.ItemTemplate>
</CollectionView>
```

**Key points:**

- `x:DataType="models:Product"` on the `DataTemplate` enables **compiled bindings** — resolved at compile time for better performance and compile-time error checking.
- `{x:Bind ...}` uses compiled bindings (vs `{Binding ...}` which is reflection-based).
- `CollectionView` scrolls vertically by default (`ItemsLayout="VerticalList"`).
- Add the namespace: `xmlns:models="clr-namespace:YourApp.Models"`.

**Model & ViewModel:**
```csharp
public class Product
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public decimal Price { get; set; }
}

public class MyViewModel
{
    public ObservableCollection<Product> Products { get; } = new()
    {
        new Product { Name = "Widget", Price = 9.99m },
        new Product { Name = "Gadget", Price = 24.95m }
    };
}
```

> **Note:** If you're in **.NET MAUI**, `x:Bind` isn't available — use `{Binding}` with `x:DataType` instead, which gives you **compiled bindings** in MAUI. In **WinUI 3 / UWP**, `x:Bind` is the compiled binding syntax.
